We apply the power-reducing formula twice:
$$\begin{aligned}
\cos^4\theta &= (\cos^2\theta)^2 \\
&= \left(\frac{1 + \cos 2\theta}{2}\right)^2 \\
&= \frac{1 + 2\cos 2\theta + \cos^2 2\theta}{4}
\end{aligned}$$
Now we need to reduce $\cos^2 2\theta$:
$$
\cos^2 2\theta = \frac{1 + \cos 4\theta}{2}
$$
Substituting:
$$\begin{aligned}
\cos^4\theta &= \frac{1 + 2\cos 2\theta + \frac{1 + \cos 4\theta}{2}}{4} \\
&= \frac{2 + 4\cos 2\theta + 1 + \cos 4\theta}{8} \\
&= \frac{3 + 4\cos 2\theta + \cos 4\theta}{8}
\end{aligned}$$

We use the tangent half-angle formula with $\theta = \frac{\pi}{4}$:
$$
\tan\frac{\pi}{8} = \tan\frac{\pi/4}{2} = \frac{1 - \cos\frac{\pi}{4}}{\sin\frac{\pi}{4}}
= \frac{1 - \frac{\sqrt{2}}{2}}{\frac{\sqrt{2}}{2}}
$$
Simplifying:
$$
= \frac{\frac{2 - \sqrt{2}}{2}}{\frac{\sqrt{2}}{2}} = \frac{2 - \sqrt{2}}{\sqrt{2}}
= \frac{(2 - \sqrt{2})\sqrt{2}}{2} = \frac{2\sqrt{2} - 2}{2} = \sqrt{2} - 1
$$

First, determine the quadrant of $\frac{\theta}{2}$. Since $\pi < \theta < \frac{3\pi}{2}$:
$$
\frac{\pi}{2} < \frac{\theta}{2} < \frac{3\pi}{4}
$$
This means $\frac{\theta}{2}$ is in Quadrant II, where sine is positive 
and cosine is negative.

$$\begin{aligned}
\sin\frac{\theta}{2} &= +\sqrt{\frac{1 - \cos\theta}{2}} 
= +\sqrt{\frac{1 - (-\frac{4}{5})}{2}} 
= +\sqrt{\frac{9/5}{2}} = \frac{3\sqrt{10}}{10} \\[6pt]
\cos\frac{\theta}{2} &= -\sqrt{\frac{1 + \cos\theta}{2}} 
= -\sqrt{\frac{1 + (-\frac{4}{5})}{2}} 
= -\sqrt{\frac{1}{10}} = -\frac{\sqrt{10}}{10}
\end{aligned}$$

