**Double-Angle Formulas:**
$$\begin{aligned}
\sin 2\theta &= 2\sin\theta\cos\theta \\[4pt]
\cos 2\theta &= \cos^2\theta - \sin^2\theta = 1 - 2\sin^2\theta = 2\cos^2\theta - 1 \\[4pt]
\tan 2\theta &= \frac{2\tan\theta}{1 - \tan^2\theta}
\end{aligned}$$

**Half-Angle Formulas:**
$$\begin{aligned}
\sin\frac{\theta}{2} &= \pm\sqrt{\frac{1 - \cos\theta}{2}} \\[4pt]
\cos\frac{\theta}{2} &= \pm\sqrt{\frac{1 + \cos\theta}{2}} \\[4pt]
\tan\frac{\theta}{2} &= \frac{1 - \cos\theta}{\sin\theta} = \frac{\sin\theta}{1 + \cos\theta}
\end{aligned}$$

*Note:* The $\pm$ sign in sine and cosine half-angle formulas is determined by the quadrant in which $\frac{\theta}{2}$ lies. The tangent half-angle formulas have no $\pm$ because they can be expressed without square roots.

**Power-Reducing Formulas:**
$$\begin{aligned}
\sin^2\theta &= \frac{1 - \cos 2\theta}{2} \\[4pt]
\cos^2\theta &= \frac{1 + \cos 2\theta}{2} \\[4pt]
\tan^2\theta &= \frac{1 - \cos 2\theta}{1 + \cos 2\theta}
\end{aligned}$$
